# RAG-pipeline-for-medical-Q-A


Excited to share a project I built as part of the Generative AI and AI Application module at Warwick Business School 🎓
I designed and implemented a Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) pipeline for medical Q&A, using a weighted Reciprocal Rank Fusion (RRF) approach to improve how relevant evidence is retrieved and ranked before being passed to the model.
Key results vs. the baseline RAG system: 
📈 +65% overall performance (combined precision, MRR, NDCG) 
🎯 +82% improvement in exact match accuracy 
🔍 +56% improvement in retrieval precision 
📊 +13.83% improvement in ranking quality (MRR)
🧭 +4.59% improvement in relevance ranking (NDCG)
Beyond the numbers, this project pushed me to think like both an analyst and an auditor: testing where the system's evidence held up, where it didn't, and being honest about the gaps — like the recall trade-off, and the challenges complex medical terminology and multi-step clinical reasoning still pose for retrieval systems.

Next steps I'm exploring: domain-specific embeddings, knowledge graph-based entity linking, and multi-hop retrieval to handle more complex questions.
Grateful for the chance to apply Gen AI concepts to a real, imperfect problem — and for what it taught me about the gap between "improved" and "solved."
